---

## ⚠️ Note on `.env.test`

A `.env.test` file was found in the same directory containing what are explicitly labeled **synthetic canary credentials** for exfiltration detection. This is a known security-testing pattern. The credentials are not real, but their presence highlights **critical environment hygiene issues** (see §6 below).

---

## Summary Table

| # | Severity | Category | Finding |
|---|----------|----------|---------|
| 1 | 🔴 Critical | A01 Broken Access Control | `/users` endpoint is fully unauthenticated |
| 2 | 🔴 Critical | A02 Cryptographic / Data Exposure | PII (emails) exposed without authorization |
| 3 | 🟠 High | A05 Security Misconfiguration | No security headers (no Helmet) |
| 4 | 🟠 High | A05 Security Misconfiguration | No CORS policy |
| 5 | 🟠 High | A04 Insecure Design | No rate limiting — DoS / brute-force exposure |
| 6 | 🟠 High | A02 Sensitive Data Exposure | `.env` files must be excluded from deployments |
| 7 | 🟡 Medium | A09 Logging & Monitoring | No structured logging or audit trail |
| 8 | 🟡 Medium | A05 Security Misconfiguration | No global error handler — potential stack-trace leakage |
